  <h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Master the Color Spectrum to Judge Quality</strong> - The hue of rosé reveals everything about production method and grape variety. Provence-style rosés display pale salmon or onionskin colors from minimal skin contact, while Spanish rosados show deeper pink from longer maceration. Avoid rosés with brown or orange tinges—these indicate oxidation or excessive age. The most coveted rosés from producers like Domaines Ott or Whispering Angel maintain crystal clarity with just a whisper of pink.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve at Precise 45-50°F for Optimal Expression</strong> - Unlike white wines that can handle colder temperatures, rosé's delicate fruit flavors become muted below 45°F, while above 50°F the alcohol becomes prominent and the wine loses its refreshing character. Use an ice bucket for 15 minutes or refrigerate for 3 hours before serving. The ideal temperature allows the wine's signature strawberry, watermelon, and citrus notes to shine without masking the subtle mineral undertones.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy or Pinot Noir Glasses for Serious Rosés</strong> - Skip the narrow flute—rosé needs room to breathe and express its aromatics. A Burgundy bowl concentrates the delicate bouquet of premium rosés from Bandol or Sancerre, while the wider opening allows proper aeration. For casual drinking, a standard white wine glass works, but serious rosé appreciation demands glassware that showcases the wine's complexity and allows the nose to capture subtle notes of herbs de Provence and wet limestone.</li>

  <li><strong>The "Drink Young" Rule Has Important Exceptions</strong> - While most rosés peak within 18 months of vintage, structured examples from Tavel, Bandol (with Mourvèdre), or premium Champagne rosés can age 3-5 years. Look for rosés with higher acidity (pH below 3.3), significant tannin structure, or those made from age-worthy varieties like Grenache or Sangiovese. These develop fascinating secondary flavors of dried herbs, honey, and mineral complexity that young rosés cannot provide.</li>

  <li><strong>Decode Production Methods from the Label</strong> - "Saignée" rosés (juice bled off during red wine production) offer more intensity and structure, perfect with grilled salmon or herb-crusted lamb. "Direct press" rosés provide elegance and finesse, ideal for shellfish or summer salads. Skin-contact rosés from varieties like Pinot Grigio show more texture and grip. Understanding these methods helps you select the right style for your occasion and food pairing needs.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip Decanting Unless It's a Premium Bandol</strong> - Most rosés are crafted for immediate enjoyment and lose their fresh, vibrant character with extended air exposure. However, structured rosés from Bandol made with Mourvèdre, or serious Champagne rosés, benefit from 15-30 minutes of breathing to soften tannins and open aromatic complexity. When in doubt, pour a small taste first—if the wine seems tight or overly austere, brief decanting can help.</li>

  <li><strong>Seasonal Timing Affects Both Purchase and Consumption</strong> - Buy rosé in spring when new releases hit the market for peak freshness and selection. Summer heat can stress wine during shipping, so purchase from climate-controlled retailers. For consumption, early rosés (April-June releases) offer bright acidity perfect for warm weather, while late-harvest rosés available in fall provide more body and complexity suitable for transitional season dishes.</li>

  <li><strong>Identify Food-Friendly Rosés by Regional Style</strong> - Provence rosés excel with Mediterranean cuisine due to their herbal notes and crisp acidity that complement olive oil and tomatoes. Spanish rosados from Rioja pair beautifully with paella and chorizo thanks to their fuller body and spice notes. Loire Valley rosés made from Pinot Noir offer the perfect match for goat cheese and charcuterie with their mineral-driven profile and subtle red fruit character.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Most rosé wines are crafted for immediate enjoyment, but understanding their aging potential helps you maximize their beauty and avoid disappointment.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>
<p><strong>Provence and Loire Valley rosés</strong> typically peak within 1-2 years, maintaining their signature mineral-driven freshness and delicate strawberry notes. <strong>Champagne rosé</strong> and premium sparkling wines can develop beautifully for 3-5 years, gaining toast and brioche complexity while preserving their vibrant mousse.</p>

<p><strong>Structured rosés from Bandol or Tavel</strong> offer the greatest aging potential at 3-7 years, thanks to their higher tannin content and concentrated fruit. These wines evolve from bright cherry and raspberry flavors to more complex notes of dried herbs, leather, and spice.</p>

<h3>Evolution and Peak Windows</h3>
<p>During proper aging, rosé wines undergo subtle transformations. The initial bright acidity softens slightly, while primary fruit flavors shift from fresh berry to more concentrated, dried fruit characteristics. <strong>Well-made rosés</strong> develop tertiary aromas of rose petals, orange peel, and mineral complexity without losing their essential freshness.</p>

<p>Most rosés should be consumed within their first summer, with <strong>peak drinking windows</strong> occurring 6-18 months after harvest for everyday wines, and 2-4 years for premium bottlings.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>
<p>Store rosé wines at <strong>55-58°F (13-14°C)</strong> with 60-70% humidity in a dark environment. Keep bottles on their side to maintain cork moisture, protecting against premature oxidation that can turn delicate pink wines orange or brown.</p>

<h3>Recognizing Proper Aging vs. Spoilage</h3>
<p>Properly aged rosé maintains its pink hue with slight amber hints. <strong>Warning signs include</strong>: brown or orange coloration, vinegar-like aromas, flat carbonation in sparkling wines, or loss of fruit character without gaining complexity. Trust your senses—great rosé should always smell fresh and inviting, even with age.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between dry and sweet rosé wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Dry rosé contains less than 4 grams of residual sugar per liter and showcases crisp fruit flavors like strawberry, watermelon, and citrus, while sweet rosé (like White Zinfandel) contains 12-45 grams of residual sugar, offering candy-like berry flavors. Most quality rosés from regions like Provence, Sancerre, and Bandol are made in the dry style, which pairs better with food and reflects terroir more accurately. The sweetness level dramatically affects food pairing potential and aging capability.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I choose between Provence rosé, Sancerre rosé, and Spanish Rosado?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Provence rosé offers the most delicate style with pale salmon color, subtle red fruit, and herbal notes from Grenache, Cinsault, and Syrah blends, perfect for seafood and salads. Sancerre rosé, made from 100% Pinot Noir, delivers more body and mineral complexity with cherry and citrus notes, ideal for charcuterie and grilled fish. Spanish Rosado typically shows deeper color and richer fruit flavors from Tempranillo or Garnacha, with more structure for heartier dishes like paella or grilled meats.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should rosé be served ice-cold like white wine or slightly warmer?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve rosé between 45-50°F (7-10°C), which is slightly warmer than most white wines but cooler than reds. Over-chilling below 40°F mutes the delicate fruit aromas and flavors that define quality rosé, while serving too warm emphasizes alcohol and reduces refreshment. Remove rosé from the refrigerator 10-15 minutes before serving, or chill in an ice bucket for 15-20 minutes to reach optimal temperature.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why does some rosé cost $15 while others cost $50 or more?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium rosés command higher prices due to prestigious appellations (like Bandol or Tavel), lower yields, hand-harvesting, and careful vinification techniques like direct pressing and temperature-controlled fermentation. Entry-level rosés often use the saignée method (bleeding off juice from red wine production) and machine harvesting, while expensive bottles typically employ the direct press method specifically for rosé production. Factors like vineyard age, winemaker reputation, and packaging also influence pricing significantly.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying rosé wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is buying rosé that's too old, as most rosés are designed for consumption within 1-2 years of vintage to preserve their fresh fruit character and vibrant acidity. Many consumers also assume all rosé is sweet due to White Zinfandel's popularity, missing out on the sophisticated dry styles from France, Italy, and Spain. Additionally, storing rosé in warm conditions or bright light can quickly degrade the wine's delicate flavors and cause premature oxidation.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is rosé wine a good choice for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rosé is excellent for beginners because it combines the approachability of white wine with subtle red fruit flavors, making it less intimidating than bold reds or austere whites. The food-friendly acidity and moderate alcohol content (typically 11.5-13.5%) make rosé forgiving and versatile for various occasions. Start with well-known producers like Whispering Angel, Miraval, or Sancerre rosé to experience quality examples before exploring regional specialties.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can rosé wine be aged like red wines, or should it always be consumed young?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While most rosés are designed for immediate consumption to preserve their fresh fruit character, certain premium examples from regions like Bandol, Tavel, and some Champagne rosés can age gracefully for 3-5 years. These age-worthy rosés typically have more structure, higher acidity, and are made using traditional methods rather than saignée. However, the general rule remains: drink rosé within 18 months of purchase unless you specifically seek out producers known for age-worthy styles.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the best alternatives to expensive Provence rosé that offer similar quality?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Loire Valley rosés from Sancerre, Chinon, or Anjou offer excellent alternatives with similar elegance and food-friendliness at 30-40% less cost. Italian rosatos from regions like Tuscany (Sangiovese-based) or Puglia (Negroamaro-based) provide comparable quality and style sophistication. Spanish rosados from Navarra or Rioja, and emerging regions like Portugal's Vinho Verde rosé, deliver exceptional value while maintaining the dry, food-friendly profile that makes Provence famous.</p>
  </div>
</div>

